  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in most jurisdictions, including the United States. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\") by concealing the true source, ownership, or destination of the funds. This is typically done through a series of complex financial transactions.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is prosecuted under federal law, primarily under the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957). Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- Significant fines (up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater),\n- Imprisonment (up to 20 years per count),\n- Seizure of assets involved in the laundering scheme,\n- Additional civil penalties.\n\nThe severity of the punishment often depends on the amount of money laundered, the nature of the underlying criminal activity (e.g., drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud), and the defendant\u2019s role in the scheme. Additionally, many states have their own money laundering laws that can result in separate charges and penalties.\n\nIf you or someone you know is facing allegations of money laundering, it is crucial to seek legal advice from an experienced attorney to understand the charges and potential defenses.",
